You said
 Fio using Por Performance testing right, what is the Fio engine you are using is it synchronous or asynchronous give a short answer ?

Gemini said
Whether FIO is synchronous or asynchronous depends entirely on the ioengine parameter you define in your job file or command line.

Synchronous: If you use ioengine=psync, sync, or vsync, FIO is synchronous. It issues one I/O request and waits for it to complete before sending the next.

Asynchronous: If you use ioengine=libaio (Linux) or ioengine=windowsaio (Windows), FIO is asynchronous. It allows you to submit multiple I/O requests simultaneously, defined by the iodepth parameter.

For high-performance NVMe testing (like your Micron validation work), asynchronous engines are almost always used to saturate the drive's bandwidth and test its queue depth capabilities.
