ssd nvme spec related i want run wearleveling test case on the drive explain me the process of the wearleveling in ssd nvme protocol level ?

Gemini said
To understand wear leveling at the NVMe protocol level, you first have to look at the physical reality of NAND flash: each memory cell has a limited number of Program/Erase (P/E) cycles. If you write to the same physical spot repeatedly, that spot dies, even if the rest of the drive is brand new.

Wear leveling is the process of mapping logical addresses to different physical locations to ensure all NAND cells age at the same rate.

1. The Core Mechanism: Logical to Physical Mapping
Unlike a Hard Drive, an SSD never writes data to the same physical location twice in a row. NVMe uses a Flash Translation Layer (FTL) to manage a mapping table.

Host Perspective: The host (your Python script or OS) sends a Write command to LBA (Logical Block Address) 500.

Controller Perspective: The NVMe controller looks at the Wear Leveling Count of its physical blocks. It picks the "freshest" block (e.g., Physical Block 2000) and writes the data there.

The Map: The FTL updates the table: LBA 500 now lives at Physical Block 2000.

2. Types of Wear Leveling
At the protocol level, the controller manages two distinct strategies:

Dynamic Wear Leveling
This handles "hot" data (data that is frequently changed).

When the host overwrites an LBA, the controller simply picks a new, low-wear empty block for the new data.

The old physical block is marked "invalid" and eventually cleaned by Garbage Collection.

Static Wear Leveling
This is the more complex part. Some data is "cold" (like an OS file that never changes). It sits in a physical block forever, while other blocks are wearing out.

The controller will periodically move this "cold" data to a high-wear block.

This frees up the "low-wear block" (the fresh one) to be used for active writing.

3. NVMe Protocol Level Indicators
While the Wear Leveling algorithm is internal to the SSD firmware (the "Black Box"), the NVMe protocol provides specific ways to monitor and test it.

SMART / Health Information (Log Page 02h)
To verify wear leveling is working during a test, you pull the SMART/Health Information log. Key fields include:

Percentage Used: A vendor-specific estimate of the drive life consumed.

Data Units Written: To track how much "stress" you've applied.

Vendor Specific Log Pages: Most enterprise drives (Samsung, Western Digital, Intel) have hidden log pages that show the Min/Max/Avg Erase Counts.

The Write/Trim Cycle
At the protocol level, wear leveling is triggered by:

Write Commands: Forcing the FTL to pick new blocks.

Dataset Management (Trim): Telling the controller which blocks are no longer needed, allowing the wear leveling engine to reclaim them.

4. Designing your Test Case
If you are writing a test case (likely in Python using a tool like nvme-cli or a custom driver), your process should look like this:

Step 1: Baseline
Query the SMART log to get the current Percentage Used and Erase Counts (if vendor-specific tools are available).

Bash
nvme smart-log /dev/nvme0n1
Step 2: Stress (The "Workout")
Run continuous random writes across the entire LBA range. This forces the controller to cycle through all physical blocks.

Note: To test Static wear leveling, you should fill 50% of the drive with data and leave it there, then hammer the remaining 50% with writes.

Step 3: Verification
Check for Uniformity: After massive writes, the Min and Max Erase counts in the vendor logs should stay close together. If Max is 1000 and Min is 10, wear leveling is failing.

WAF (Write Amplification Factor) Calculation:

WAF= 
Host Writes
Total NAND Writes
​
 
A high WAF during wear leveling tests often indicates the controller is moving static data efficiently (which is good for longevity but impacts performance).

Step 4: Data Integrity
Ensure that after the controller moves data around in the background (Static Wear Leveling), the LBA still returns the correct data.

Technical Tip for your NVMe Prep
Since you've been looking into NVMe and PCIe protocols, remember that Wear Leveling is an Internal Management task. The host doesn't tell the SSD how to wear level; the host provides the "idle time" (via the NVMe Power States) or the "intent" (via Trim) for the SSD to perform these background tasks.

what about stability level pure io

Gemini said
When you talk about "Stability Level Pure IO" in the context of SSD NVMe testing, you are essentially looking at the Steady State performance. This is the point where the drive’s internal management (Wear Leveling, Garbage Collection, and NAND management) balances out with the incoming host commands.

In a Wear Leveling test, "Stability" means that the performance doesn't "jitter" or drop off a cliff because the controller is too busy moving static data around.

1. The Three Stages of IO Stability
To test wear leveling stability, you must push the drive through these three phases:

Fresh Out of Box (FOB): The drive is empty. IO is fast and stable because the controller just picks the next empty block.

Transition Phase: The drive fills up. The controller starts realizing it has to erase old blocks before it can write new ones. You will see performance "spikes" and "dips."

Steady State (The Stability Goal): The drive reaches a plateau. The Wear Leveling engine is working at a constant rate. This is where you measure your test results.

2. Testing Pure IO Stability for Wear Leveling
To verify that Wear Leveling isn't causing instability, you should focus on these protocol-level metrics:

IOPS Consistency
If you are running a 100% Random Write workload, a "stable" drive should have a tight standard deviation. If the IOPS fluctuates by more than 10%, it suggests the Wear Leveling algorithm is "clogging" the pipeline (i.e., it's moving a massive chunk of static data all at once rather than doing it smoothly in the background).

Latency Outliers (Tail Latency)
In NVMe specs, we look at the 99.9th percentile (p99.9) latency.

The Test: While the drive is performing Wear Leveling, measure how long a single IO takes.

The Stability Issue: If the controller decides to move a "cold" block (Static Wear Leveling) exactly when a host Write command arrives, that Write will be delayed. If your p99.9 latency is significantly higher than your average, the Wear Leveling implementation is "unstable."

3. Key NVMe Commands for IO Stability Tests
To achieve "Pure IO" stability during your test, you need to use these specific protocol features:

Write Uncorrectable: Used to mark blocks as "bad" or "dead" to see how the Wear Leveling handles "holes" in the NAND.

Dataset Management (ADPC - Attributes): Use the Integral Dataset bit. This tells the controller that the data you are writing should be treated as a single unit, which helps the Wear Leveling engine group data together and reduces background movement.

Format NVM (Secure Erase): Always start your stability test with a Format command to reset the FTL (Flash Translation Layer) to a known zero-state.

4. How to Measure "Stability" in Python/CLI
If you are automating this test, you can calculate the Stability Metric using this formula:

Stability %=( 
Average IOPS in Steady State
Minimum IOPS in Steady State
​
 )×100
Industry Standard: An enterprise-grade NVMe drive should maintain > 90% stability during a sustained Pure IO wear leveling test.

Summary for your Test Case
To prove the drive is stable:

Pre-condition: Write to the drive at 2x its capacity to ensure it is in Steady State.

Run IO: 4KB Random Writes for at least 1 hour.

Monitor: Use nvme smart-log to ensure "Percentage Used" increases linearly and iostat to ensure the IOPS curve is a flat line, not a sawtooth wave.

Since you are preparing for companies like Qualcomm or NVIDIA, they value candidates who understand that "performance" isn't just about speed—it's about consistency over thousands of hours of wear.

