i will check pcie version like gen3 or gen4 wheter it capable to handle the speed or not using lspci ?

Gemini said
Exactly. That is the correct first step in a hardware validation or troubleshooting scenario. If a Gen 4 drive is performing at Gen 3 speeds, you are likely looking at a link negotiation issue.

Using lspci is the standard way to verify this in Linux. Here is how you would break that down during an interview to show you know your way around the command line:

1. Identify the Device
First, you need the Bus/Device/Function (BDF) address of the NVMe drive:

Bash
lspci | grep -i nvme
Output example: 01:00.0 Non-Volatile memory controller...

2. Check the "Link Capabilities" vs. "Link Status"
This is the most important part. You use the -vvv (very verbose) flag and look for the LnkCap and LnkSta sections.

Bash
sudo lspci -s 01:00.0 -vvv | grep -E "LnkCap:|LnkSta:"
LnkCap (Link Capabilities): This tells you what the hardware is physically capable of (e.g., Speed 16GT/s for Gen 4, Width x4).

LnkSta (Link Status): This tells you what the link is currently running at.

The Interview Answer: > "If LnkCap shows Speed 16GT/s (Gen 4) but LnkSta shows Speed 8GT/s (Gen 3), I know the link failed to train at the highest supported speed. This could be due to a poor physical connection, signal integrity issues on the PCB, or a BIOS setting limiting the PCIe generation."

Pro-Tip: Decoding the Speeds
Interviewers might ask you what "GT/s" (Gigatransfers per second) translates to in PCIe Generations. It's helpful to have these memorized:

Gen 3: 8 GT/s

Gen 4: 16 GT/s

Gen 5: 32 GT/s

One more thing to check: dmesg
If lspci shows a downgraded link, you should immediately follow up by checking the kernel ring buffer to see if there were any "AER" (Advanced Error Reporting) messages:

Bash
dmesg | grep -i pcie | grep -i error
This shows if the system tried to go to Gen 4 but "fell back" to Gen 3 because of too many transmission errors.

