Q: what is the difference between NOR flash and NAND falsh in ssd why we are using NAND ?

Gemini said
While both are types of non-volatile memory, they are built with different internal architectures that make them excel at very different tasks. Think of NOR as a library where you can walk straight to a specific page of a book, and NAND as a warehouse where you move entire boxes at a time.

The Core Differences
The names "NOR" and "NAND" refer to the type of logic gate used to store data. This physical layout dictates how the memory is accessed.

Feature	NOR Flash	NAND Flash
Access Method	Random Access (Byte-level)	Page/Block Access
Read Speed	Very Fast	Fast
Write/Erase Speed	Slow	Very Fast
Density/Capacity	Low (Small storage)	High (Massive storage)
Cost per Bit	High	Low
Durability	High (100k - 1M cycles)	Lower (3k - 100k cycles)
1. NOR Flash: The "Execution" Memory
In NOR flash, the cells are connected in parallel. This allows the CPU to access any specific memory address directly, just like RAM.

Best for: Storing code that needs to be executed directly from the chip (e.g., BIOS, UEFI, or firmware for a router).

Why not for SSDs? It is physically "bulky." You can’t pack many cells into a small space, making high-capacity drives impossibly expensive and large.

2. NAND Flash: The "Storage" Memory
In NAND flash, cells are connected in series. You cannot access a single byte; you must read or write an entire Page (usually 4KB or 8KB).

Best for: Large files, photos, videos, and operating systems.

Why it's in SSDs: It is incredibly dense. You can stack NAND cells vertically (3D NAND), allowing for terabytes of data in a chip the size of a fingernail.

Why SSDs Exclusively Use NAND
If you tried to build a 1TB SSD using NOR flash, it would likely be the size of a briefcase and cost as much as a luxury car. We use NAND for three primary reasons:

1. Density and Scalability
NAND flash cells take up much less physical "real estate" on the silicon wafer than NOR cells. Modern 3D NAND technology stacks hundreds of layers of memory cells on top of each other. This is what allows modern laptops to have 2TB or 4TB of storage in such a slim frame.

2. Write and Erase Performance
While NOR is great at reading, it is painfully slow at writing and erasing. NAND is optimized for "bursting" data. When you save a large video file, NAND can write those "blocks" of data much faster than NOR ever could.

3. Cost Efficiency
Because NAND is denser, the "cost per gigabyte" is significantly lower. This economy of scale is what made SSDs affordable enough to replace traditional spinning Hard Disk Drives (HDDs).

Summary in the Context of Your Laptop
Your BIOS/UEFI chip is likely NOR Flash because the laptop needs to read that code instantly to start up, and the file size is very small (usually 16MB to 32MB).

Your SSD is NAND Flash because you need to store hundreds of gigabytes of data cheaply and save files quickly.

